  "texts": [
    "The equivalence notion for solutions of (4) is motivated by the link with Riemannian metrics on twisted principal bundles, and is made precise in Definition 3.5 (see also Proposition 2.15).",
    "We emphasise that Theorem C holds for any symmetric space G/K of non-positive curvature, and is not restricted to those arising from the soliton construction as in (5).Theorems A and C yield the following consequence, which is our main tool for producing examples of expanding Ricci solitons by using Higgs bundles:Corollary D. Given a closed Riemann surface Σ = (B 2, c) of genus at least 2, there is a finite-to-one correspondence between polystable G 0 -Higgs bundles (P, Φ) over Σ with tr Φ 2 = 0, up to equivalence and pullback by Aut(Σ), and affine expanding Ricci solitons on twisted principal bundles B × ρ N → B with ρ(π 1 (B)) ≤ G 0 and inducing the conformal structure c on B, up to isometric bundle maps.",
    "Here, G 0 is the identity component of the group G defined in (5).The restriction to solitons with monodromy into the identity component G 0 in Corollary D is due to a technicality in the literature on the non-abelian Hodge correspondence, and we do not expect it to be essential.",
    "We note that, up to passing to a finite cover B → B and pulling back the bundle M → B to B, the assumption ρ(π 1 (B)) ≤ G 0 is always satisfied; see the discussion in Section 4.2.The Higgs field Φ is intimately related to dh, and the condition tr Φ 2 = 0 is well-known to be equivalent to h being weakly conformal (also called a branched minimal immersion).",
    "In the special case where dh has full rank, h is indeed a minimal immersion of B into the symmetric space G/K."
  ],
